<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="234" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,510,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,510,535]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In the 
<taxonomicName box="[361,475,511,534]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hippasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="partita">
<emphasis box="[361,475,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">H. partita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, the bifurcation of the two arms of the median apophysis is usually located proximally and may even be invisible in the ventral view of the palp (
<figureCitation box="[1025,1096,546,571]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[171,1411,848,1705]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[161,1426,838,1720]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Hippasa lycosina Pocock, 1900. A. Left male pedipalp, ventral view; B. Same, retrolateral view; C. Epigyne, ventral view; D. Same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: AA, anterior arm of median apophysis; At, atrium; Co, conductor; CO, copulatory opening; Em, embolus; FD, fertilization duct; HS, head of spermatheca; PA, posterior arm of median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermatheca; St, subtegulum; TA, terminal apophysis (= synembolus sensu Zyuzin (1993 )); Te, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243946/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">
Figs 
<number box="[1082,1096,547,571]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[1131,1145,547,571]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="8.0">8</number>
C). The anterior arm (
<emphasis box="[1392,1426,547,570]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">AA</emphasis>
) is curved and usually sickle or hook-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[667,740,582,607]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[171,1411,848,1705]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[161,1426,838,1720]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Hippasa lycosina Pocock, 1900. A. Left male pedipalp, ventral view; B. Same, retrolateral view; C. Epigyne, ventral view; D. Same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: AA, anterior arm of median apophysis; At, atrium; Co, conductor; CO, copulatory opening; Em, embolus; FD, fertilization duct; HS, head of spermatheca; PA, posterior arm of median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermatheca; St, subtegulum; TA, terminal apophysis (= synembolus sensu Zyuzin (1993 )); Te, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243946/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">
Figs 
<number box="[725,740,583,606]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B, 
<number box="[774,788,583,607]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="8.0">8</number>
D). The epigyne lacks a scape but has an obvious atrium (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,618,643]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[171,1411,848,1705]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[161,1426,838,1720]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Hippasa lycosina Pocock, 1900. A. Left male pedipalp, ventral view; B. Same, retrolateral view; C. Epigyne, ventral view; D. Same, dorsal view. Abbreviations: AA, anterior arm of median apophysis; At, atrium; Co, conductor; CO, copulatory opening; Em, embolus; FD, fertilization duct; HS, head of spermatheca; PA, posterior arm of median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermatheca; St, subtegulum; TA, terminal apophysis (= synembolus sensu Zyuzin (1993 )); Te, tegulum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/243946/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">
Figs 
<number box="[215,229,619,643]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[262,275,619,643]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234" value="8.0">8</number>
Eâ€“F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,510,679]" box="[199,1011,654,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,559,654,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="234">Composition and distribution.</emphasis>
Seventeen species are included (
